  1. Briefly describe what Bash commands zcat, zless, zmore, and zgrep do.

zcat: Similar to cat, it displays the contents of gzip-compressed files to the standard output. Useful for viewing compressed text files without decompressing them first.

zless: Works like less, allowing you to page through compressed text files one screen at a time. Itâs helpful for reading large compressed files without decompressing them entirely.

zmore: Similar to more, it lets you view compressed files page by page, but with less functionality compared to zless.

zgrep: Combines grep functionality with gzip compression, enabling you to search inside compressed files without decompressing them first.

The admission_type variable in the MIMIC-IV database includes several categories. Some of these are âELECTIVEâ, âURGENTâ, and various types of âOBSERVATIONâ and âEMERGENCYâ admissions.

  1. To compress, or not to compress. Thatâs the question. Letâs focus on the big data file labevents.csv.gz. Compare compressed gz file size to the uncompressed file size. Compare the run times of zcat < ~/mimic/labevents.csv.gz | wc -l versus wc -l labevents.csv. Discuss the trade off between storage and speed for big data files. (Hint: gzip -dk < FILENAME.gz > ./FILENAME. Remember to delete the large labevents.csv file after the exercise.)

ls -lh ~/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz
-rwxrwxrwx 1 eewol123 eewol123 1.9G Jan 25 21:45 /home/eewol123/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz

gzip -dk ~/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz

ls -lh ~/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv
-rwxrwxrwx 1 eewol123 eewol123 13G Jan 26 00:42 /home/eewol123/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv
zcat ~/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz | wc -l
rm ~/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz

Compressed files (gzip) take up significantly less storage space.

Reading from a compressed file (zcat) is generally slower compared to an uncompressed file due to the time needed for decompression. For one-time or infrequent access, zcat is efficient as it saves storage space without needing to store a large uncompressed file. For frequent access to the data, especially random access, keeping an uncompressed version might be more efficient time-wise.

  1. You and your friend just have finished reading Pride and Prejudice by Jane Austen. Among the four main characters in the book, Elizabeth, Jane, Lydia, and Darcy, your friend thinks that Darcy was the most mentioned. You, however, are certain it was Elizabeth. Obtain the full text of the novel from http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt and save to your local folder.

wget -nc http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt
File âpg42671.txtâ already there; not retrieving.

Explain what wget -nc does. Do not put this text file pg42671.txt in Git. Complete the following loop to tabulate the number of times each of the four characters is mentioned using Linux commands.

The wget -nc command is used to download files from the internet. The -nc flag stands for âno-clobberâ, which means if a file with the same name already exists in the destination directory, it wonât be overwritten. This is useful for avoiding duplicate downloads or preserving modifications to an existing file.

wget -nc http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt
for char in Elizabeth Jane Lydia Darcy
do
  echo $char:
  grep -o $char pg42671.txt | wc -l
done
  1. Whatâs the difference between the following two commands?
echo 'hello, world' > test1.txt

and

echo 'hello, world' >> test2.txt

echo âhello, worldâ > test1.txt: This command uses the > operator, which redirects the output of the echo command to the file test1.txt. If test1.txt already exists, this command will overwrite the file with the new content (âhello, worldâ). If the file doesnât exist, it will create a new file named test1.txt containing the provided text.

echo âhello, worldâ >> test2.txt: This command uses the >> operator, which appends the output of the echo command to the file test2.txt. If test2.txt already exists, the text âhello, worldâ will be added to the end of the file, preserving its existing content. If the file doesnât exist, it will create a new file named test2.txt with the provided text.

In summary, > is used for overwriting (or creating a new file), while >> is used for appending to an existing file (or creating a new file if it doesnât exist).
